---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
import drugsData from '../../../../data/drugs.json';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const slug = 'endocrine';
const displayName = 'Endocrine & Metabolic';

const drugs = (drugsData as any[]).filter(
  (d: any) => (d.organ_systems || []).includes(slug)
);
const drugCount = drugs.length;
---
<SchemaLayout title="Endocrine & Metabolic Pharmacology" schema="organ-systems" description="Drugs classified under the Endocrine & Metabolic organ system">

  <div class="mb-6">
    <div class="breadcrumbs text-sm mb-4">
      <ul>
        <li><a href={`${base}schemas/01-organ-systems/`} class="link">Organ Systems</a></li>
        <li>Endocrine & Metabolic</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-base-content mb-2">Endocrine & Metabolic</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">{drugCount} drug{drugCount !== 1 ? 's' : ''} in this system</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>The endocrine system presents a pharmacological landscape defined by receptor agonism and antagonism, enzyme inhibition, and hormone replacement -- strategies that require precision dosing because the endogenous hormones themselves function within narrow physiological windows. Major drug targets include insulin receptors and glucose transporters for diabetes management, thyroid hormone nuclear receptors, corticosteroid receptors (glucocorticoid, mineralocorticoid, androgen, and estrogen receptors), pituitary peptide receptors (GnRH, GH, ACTH), and the calcium-sensing receptor. The endocrine system also includes metabolic targets of the newer diabetes drug classes: SGLT2 in the proximal tubule, GLP-1 receptors in the pancreatic beta cell and hypothalamus, and DPP-4 enzyme that degrades incretin hormones. Disease states include type 1 and type 2 diabetes, hypothyroidism, hyperthyroidism, adrenal insufficiency, Cushing's syndrome, hypoparathyroidism, osteoporosis, and pituitary disorders. Nursing priorities include glucose monitoring frequency and targets, recognition of hypoglycemia and thyroid storm, corticosteroid sick-day rules, and patient education about the life-sustaining nature of hormone replacement.</p>
    <p>Insulin therapy for type 1 diabetes and insulin-requiring type 2 diabetes requires understanding of pharmacokinetic profiles across analog formulations. Rapid-acting analogs (lispro, aspart, glulisine) have onset of 10 to 15 minutes and must be given within 15 minutes of a meal; NPH insulin (intermediate-acting) has unpredictable peak activity and a higher hypoglycemia risk than the long-acting analogs glargine, detemir, and degludec. Glargine and degludec form subcutaneous microprecipitates that dissolve slowly, providing 24 to 42 hours of peakless basal coverage. Nurses must rotate injection sites systematically to prevent lipohypertrophy, never mix glargine with other insulins due to pH incompatibility, and treat any blood glucose below 70 mg/dL with 15 grams of fast-acting carbohydrates. GLP-1 receptor agonists (liraglutide, semaglutide, dulaglutide, tirzepatide) stimulate glucose-dependent insulin secretion, suppress glucagon, slow gastric emptying, and reduce appetite; their cardiovascular and renal outcome benefits are now guideline-endorsed in type 2 diabetes with established cardiovascular disease or CKD.</p>
    <p>Thyroid pharmacology divides into replacement therapy and synthesis inhibition. Levothyroxine (T4), the cornerstone of hypothyroid replacement, has a narrow therapeutic window and multiple drug-drug interactions; it must be taken on an empty stomach 30 to 60 minutes before breakfast, separated from calcium, iron, aluminum-containing compounds, and cholestyramine by at least four hours. TSH is the monitoring parameter, with a target of 0.5 to 2.5 mIU/L for most patients; changes in dose require six to eight weeks before TSH reaches a new steady state. Methimazole and propylthiouracil (PTU) inhibit thyroid peroxidase to block iodide organification; PTU additionally inhibits peripheral T4-to-T3 conversion and is preferred in thyroid storm and the first trimester of pregnancy. Agranulocytosis is a rare but life-threatening effect of both thioamides; patients must be instructed to report fever or sore throat immediately and present for CBC. Glucocorticoid pharmacology encompasses both replacement doses in adrenal insufficiency and pharmacological doses for anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive indications, with the critical nursing responsibility of never abruptly discontinuing chronic corticosteroid therapy due to hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis suppression.</p>
  </div>

  {drugs.length === 0 && (
    <div class="alert alert-info mb-6">
      <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path></svg>
      <span>No drugs are currently classified under this organ system. Check back as more drug data is added.</span>
    </div>
  )}

  {drugs.length > 0 && (
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      {drugs.map((drug: any) => (
        <div class={`card card-compact bg-base-100 shadow border border-base-200 ${drug.ismp_high_alert ? 'border-l-4 border-l-error' : ''}`}>
          <div class="card-body">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-start gap-1 mb-1">
              <h2 class="card-title text-base font-semibold capitalize mr-auto">
                <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">
                  {drug.generic_name}
                </a>
              </h2>
              {drug.prototype_for && (
                <span class="badge badge-success badge-sm shrink-0">PROTOTYPE</span>
              )}
              {drug.ismp_high_alert && (
                <span class="badge badge-error badge-sm shrink-0">HIGH ALERT</span>
              )}
              {drug.black_box_warnings && drug.black_box_warnings.length > 0 && (
                <span class="badge badge-warning badge-sm shrink-0">BBW</span>
              )}
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-base-content/60 mb-1">
              <span class="font-medium">{drug.drug_class}</span>
              {drug.subclass && <span> &mdash; {drug.subclass}</span>}
            </p>
            {drug.mechanism_summary && (
              <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70 line-clamp-3">{drug.mechanism_summary}</p>
            )}
            <div class="card-actions justify-end mt-2">
              <a href={`${base}drugs/${drug.id}/`} class="btn btn-xs btn-outline btn-primary">Profile</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  )}

</SchemaLayout>
